#転送 [[石上宅嗣#経歴]]

{{Coord|34|35|17.40|N|135|51|4.73|E|region:JP-29_type:landmark|display=title|name=杣之内火葬墓}}
{{DEFAULTSORT:そまのうちかそうほ}}
[[Category:奈良県の考古遺跡]]
[[Category:天理市の歴史]]
[[Category:奈良時代の遺跡]]

'''Somanouchi Cremation Tomb''' (杣之内火葬墓) is an [[8th century]] [[cremation tomb]] located in {{ill|Tenri, Nara|ja|天理市}}, [[Nara Prefecture]], Japan. It is not designated as a historic site.

== Overview ==

The tomb is situated on the southern slope of a hill extending from Sonobara-cho to Ikusaka Pond on the eastern edge of the Nara Basin{{Sfn|Mononobe Clan's Tombs: Somanouchi Burial Mounds|2021}}. Excavations were conducted in [[1981]] (Showa 56) during the construction of a sports field{{Sfn|Hino Hiroshi|2021}}.

The tomb features a semi-circular area with a diameter of 10.36 meters and a depth of 1.5 meters, which was first excavated (first stage), backfilled with tamped earth, and then a burial pit (second stage) was dug. A wooden chest containing cremated remains was placed within the burial pit{{Sfn|Mononobe Clan's Tombs: Somanouchi Burial Mounds|2021}}{{Sfn|Hino Hiroshi|2021}}. The tamped earth consists of alternating layers of sandy soil and clay, forming a sturdy structure. The burial pit measures 1.3 meters by 1.4 meters and has a depth of 0.9 meters{{Sfn|Mononobe Clan's Tombs: Somanouchi Burial Mounds|2021}}{{Sfn|Hino Hiroshi|2021}}. The wooden chest is made of {{ill|Koyamaki|ja|コウヤマキ}} wood, with a carved body and a cedar plank lid. The chest contained cremated bones and a silver hairpin, while outside the chest, a {{ill|Sea Creature and Grape Mirror|ja|海獣葡萄鏡}} was discovered{{Sfn|Mononobe Clan's Tombs: Somanouchi Burial Mounds|2021}}{{Sfn|Hino Hiroshi|2021}}.

The tomb is dated to the [[Nara period]] (8th century), though the exact date is unclear. The tomb is believed to belong to the Mononobe clan, who were renamed the {{ill|Isonokami clan|ja|石上氏}} around [[684]]{{Sfn|Saeki Arikiyo|National History Dictionary}}. It is thought to be the resting place of a high-ranking aristocrat from this lineage, with proposed identities including {{ill|Isonokami Maro|ja|石上麻呂}} (d. 717) or {{ill|Isonokami no Yakatsugu|ja|石上宅嗣}} (d. 781).

Additionally, three burnt soil pits have been found on the same hill, indicating that this area remained a burial ground into the [[medieval period]]{{Sfn|Hino Hiroshi|2021}}.

== Artifacts ==
[[File:Somanouchi Kasobo, artifacts.jpg|thumb|220px|right|{{center|Sea Creature and Grape Mirror}}{{small|Displayed at the {{ill|Tenri Sankokan Museum|ja|天理大学附属天理参考館}}.}}]]
* **Silver hairpin**: One piece was discovered inside the chest. It measures approximately 10 cm in length and is made of 98.6% pure silver. The hairpin was partially melted due to the heat of cremation{{Sfn|Mononobe Clan's Tombs: Somanouchi Burial Mounds|2021}}.
* **Sea Creature and Grape Mirror**: One bronze mirror was found outside the chest, near the southern wall of the burial pit. It has a diameter of 12.1 cm and is made of white bronze (67% copper, 27% tin, 4.8% lead). The mirror, believed to have been imported from Tang China, is decorated with grape vines and features six birds on the outer band, six birds and two butterflies on the inner band. It is dated to the early-to-mid 8th century{{Sfn|Mononobe Clan's Tombs: Somanouchi Burial Mounds|2021}}.

Additional items, such as iron nails, flat tiles, {{ill|Sue ware|ja|須恵器}}, and {{ill|Haji ware|ja|土師器}}, were recovered but are not considered useful for dating the tomb{{Sfn|Hino Hiroshi|2021}}.

<gallery>
Somanouchi artifacts 1.jpg|Artifacts<br/>{{small|Photographed during an exhibition at Tenri Sankokan Museum.}}
</gallery>

== Buried Individual ==

<div class="thumb tright">
 <div style="margin: 0px; padding: 2px; border: 1px solid #a2a9b1; text-align: center; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%; text-align:center; font-size:80%">
'''Isonokami Clan Genealogy'''
{{familytree/start|style="text-align:left; font-size:100%"}}
{{familytree|border=0|||||||01| 01={{ill|Isonokami Maro|ja|石上麻呂}}<br/>(Senior Second Rank, Minister of the Left, 640–717)}}
{{familytree|border=0|||||||!|}}
{{familytree|border=0|||||||01| 01={{ill|Isonokami Otomaro|ja|石上乙麻呂}}<br/>(Junior Third Rank, Middle Councillor, ?–750)}}
{{familytree|border=0|||||||!|}}
{{familytree|border=0|||||||01| 01={{ill|Isonokami no Yakatsugu|ja|石上宅嗣}}<br/>(Senior Third Rank, Councillor, 729–781)}}
{{familytree/end}}
</div></div>

The buried individual is unidentified but believed to be a high-ranking aristocrat of the Isonokami clan. Proposed identities include:

* **Isonokami no Yakatsugu** (d. 781): This theory has been suggested since the publication of the excavation report, considering the individual's high rank during the Nara period.
* **Isonokami Maro** (d. 717): This recent theory compares the tomb's scale to that of the {{ill|Kojitada no Yasumaro Cremation Tomb|ja|小治田安萬侶の墓}} (Nara City). The tomb's size, robust tamped-earth construction, and associated artifacts suggest it predates Empress Genmei's 721 decree for simpler burials{{Sfn|Hino Hiroshi|2021}}.

== Related Facilities ==
* {{ill|Tenri Sankokan Museum|ja|天理大学附属天理参考館}} (Tenri City): Houses and exhibits the Sea Creature and Grape Mirror.

